711971f-a.title: Manhattan: 30th Street - 9th Avenue
711971f-a.text:
30th Street, south side, between Tenth and Ninth AAvenues,
showing the New York Central Station. The buildings to the left
are on the north side of the street. This station was built
about 1650 and was used as a passenger station uutil the Grand
was assassinated. The building will remain standing until 1931.
May 13, 1927.
P. L. Sperr.

711975f-a.title: Manhattan: 30th Street - 9th Avenue
711975f-a.text:
30th Street, north side, west from No. 415,between Ninth and
Tenth Avenues, showing the bridge across the New York Central lines
at Tenth Avenue.
September 27, 1927.
P.L. Sperr.

711972f-a.title: Manhattan: 30th Street (West) - 9th Avenue
711972f-a.text:
435-411 West 30th Street, north side, between Tenth and
Ninth Avenues, as seen across the excavation on the south side
of the street.
April 9, 1931.
P.L. Sperr.

459-427 West 30th Street, north side, between Tenth and

April 9, 1931.

710366f-a.title: Manhattan: 9th Avenue - 30th Street (West)
710366f-a.text:
Ninth Avenue, north from W. 30th Street, as photographed from
the downtown platform of the "El." The rear of the U. S. Post Office
occupies the 31st - 32nd Street frontage. The loft structure at the
S. E. corner of 31st Street houses the New York offices of the mail
order hoie--Sears Roebuck and Company.
June 7, 1940
Views 1,2
P. L. Sperr
